The paper deals with the computation of distances between high order networks, which can be seen as a problem in data analysis and machine learning. The use of persistent homology methods to approximate these distances suggests a focus on topological data analysis, which is a subfield of data science. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also deals with the classification of networks generated by different processes, which suggests a focus on statistical learning and pattern recognition, making cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) likely sub-categories as well. Finally, the use of homological features to differentiate between communities of researchers suggests a focus on numerical analysis and optimization, making cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) a possible sub-category.
